Imagine, though, that this is the Higgs boson, because the chances of making a mistake seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is one law in this world that is absolutely inevitable, stating that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There's no way to circumvent this rule, don't even try too hard, or you'll hurt yourself.
But while particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has one law of this nature: the principle of excluding Paulie, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same point in time if they are in the same "quantum state" - a "state" is, in general terms, in some of their characteristics.
Therefore, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called farmers who wisely obey the Paulie principle.
In the other, the bosons, an abominable gang of anarchists, who have no respect for anything - at least for this principle, which means that they can end up in the same place at the same time.
According to Particle Adventure of the Berkeley Laboratory, the site reports that these bosons are divided into two groups: mezones, which we are not going to talk about here, and "particles of power," by which the main forces of nature are spread and to which the Higgs boson in some way belongs.
These are the most bosons, it should be stressed, not all the exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you're able to read this chronic, it's because of one incredibly banal boson: a photon, or a "particle of light," which is an electromagnetic courier.
Indeed, when one particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "fails" the electromagnetic field in this particular place, about like a stone thrown into a pond.
This "violation" gives rise to an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared radiation, or ultraviolet, etc.) and is nothing more than a photon - and therefore one of the "power transferors" bosons.
A more stable field
The same is true of the Higgs boson, with only the difference that if this boson were to appear, another field, the Higgs field, had to be broken.
However, the Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; it requires very and very high energy, as if it were a frozen pond, the surface of which could only shake a very large stone.
