Pay and sell without the help of banks - with Bitcoin
The exact opposite of the current exchange of money based on centrifugal banks, numbered transactions between receiving parties with processing fees.
Moreover, as often happens with these technologies, there is a clear political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, leads to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto, is both a virtual currency (but converted into dollars, euros...) and a secure BitTorrent exchange protocol that allows for the exchange of files between participants at the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered with 15,000 computers online.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoin for donations or for payment.
Bitcoin, peaking at $30 (23 euros) in June 2011, fell to $2 five months later before returning to about $10 today (the rates are listed on the bitcoincharts.com website).
Nothing special compared to the world's exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB), in its report on virtual currency published in October, was interested in the system.
He describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competitive with the dollar or the euro" and "like ordinary currencies."
Bitcoin is different from other types of virtual currencies, such as "credits" used to promote video games that are earned during the game or that can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
Facebook's social network has also developed a similar system.
But exchange operations are always controlled and processed by a central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are both bookkeepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network function?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two electronic addresses, like e-mail.
Only for each new payment can the user choose another address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information related to this transaction is signed electronically using a double key encryption system.
