Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of Ministers of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted by the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on 12 September 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has actively participated in a number of Agency projects over the following years.
But Poland began the way to outer space a long time ago.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were on space flights, but this was not always understood.
I will recall, for example, the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who, on 6 December 1933, presented to the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his pioneering work "Introduction to Space."
The ideas of a young engineer (1905) left the audience indifferent, after several years Sternfeld remembered that only Dr. Jan Hadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peltri and André Luis Hirsch Prize in France for "Introducing Space."
Dr. Jan Hadomsky (1899-1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great promoter of astronomy and space.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Hadomsky became a world-renowned space promoter, and his contribution was appreciated, inter alia, by the fact that one of the craters on the back of the Moon was named after him.
As early as 1925, a railway drone with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of the idea remained unknown, as did the details of the draft.
It is not even clear whether a missile should have been used to disperse or to brake the trolley.
Information about this dream is only known from the press of that era.
From 1933 onwards, Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The study was carried out by the Arms Engineering Section in cooperation with Professors Meichekawa Wolfke and Gustav Mojitski.
The remaining material shows that the studies have reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photovoltaic fighter rocket proposed by engineer Rogozinski appeared in a specialized press, and the following year the work of the author's "Aerial Torpedo and Aerial Bomb Missile" was released.
Both projects were developed for the military use of missile engines.
Prior to the war, all military missile projects were carried out by the Interim Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The Committee was established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the work ended with the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on space appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, it is mentioned in the November 1954 issue of "Problems," which publishes four large articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich offered to organize a space society.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already gaining momentum, and it was clear that space research was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Society of Astronautics (POA) has tried to join the International Astronautical Federation (established in 1951) and has already become a valid member of PAA in the autumn.
And next year, the first president of PAA, Kazimez Zarankewicz (1902-1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautical Federation.
He remained in office until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PAA has made a significant contribution to the development of the very successful Meteorological Missile RM (Rakieta Meteologiczna), which was the first Polish missile to carry out scientific research.
The first type of RM-1 was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The rocket, capable of crossing the distance of 1,800 metres, was about 80 cm long and weighs less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 a two-stage RM-2 rocket was tested on the Bledov Desert.
The rocket was about 1.4 m long and weighs about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the missile was already able to carry out actual scientific work: the RM-34 missile could have passed 14.5 kilometres, and its mission was to monitor the high wind.
But in 1962, further development was suspended.
The first RM-type missiles were inherited by the Meteor-1 missile developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was designed as a two-stage rocket, with a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types (marked as Meteor 1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which varied in size for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 litres, Meteor-1B 0.34 litres and Meteor-1C 0.62L.
All three types had a maximum range of 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Meteor-2 missile was developed at the Aviation Institute and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with a launch weight of 380 kg, was capable of delivering a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
Mention should also be made of Poland ' s accession to COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a COSPAR national committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos programme, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
