Rules for inflating balloons, bananas and circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which conducts an annual survey of the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to launch a competition for "the most absurd decision or project from the EU workshop."
"We were encouraged by the latest event in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 per cent quota for women in the administration of major European companies," said Pravo, the organizer of the poll, Patrick Nager.
Among the absurdities that have already been nominated is the recent decision of the European Court of Justice to combine the rate of insurance premiums for men and women.
So far, women have benefited from life insurance because, for insurance companies, they are objectively less at risk.
"The next incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be put forward by the end of this year.
The voting itself will take place until the end of February 2013," said Nager.
The EU ' s controversial orders include, for example, the mandatory addition of biocomponents to fuel, which is harmful to nature, as well as the prohibition of the use of reliable mercury gradients only because they contain relatively small quantities of hazardous substances, or the chicken cell size directive, which has significantly increased the cost of eggs this year.
There was also criticism of the de facto prohibition of the use of the term " butter butter " or the removal of classic bulbs from sales.
Qualitative bananas must be 14 centimetres long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes a decision under pressure from a commercial or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by a State or group of States (the Czech Republic is now even under threat of flight in support of its banks).
The lobby's interests are such: for example, bananas of the highest quality in the European Union should have reached a length of 14 cm and dared not be "anomal curvature."
In doing so, the European Commission justified the fact that it merely harmonized existing fragmented national rules that made trade more difficult.
The EU, despite the resistance of some States, has reduced the standards for fruit and vegetables, citing that existing directives will lead to the waste of products.
The EU regulation last year, according to which selling balloons must be warned that children under eight years of age cannot inflate them without adult supervision, may also be a candidate for the survey.
The EU has turned to American research, according to which balloons in the game are the potential cause of death of children by asphyxiation.
This restriction now applies to children under the age of 14 who are not allowed to blow into fairgrounds.
Funny ideas are born at home.
The rule concerning European officials themselves is rather absurd: anyone who holds an official position in the EU cannot use the name of Macedonia, given the sensitivity of the subject for Greece, but instead should say "BUREM" (the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The Bankovnípoplatky.com portal, in cooperation with the coalition of liberal economists, Laissez Faire, proposed for voting, in addition to a few of the above-mentioned absurd rules, such as the EU rule on the volume of food reserves in the territory of a member State.
The EU has established a maximum food stock that may be in the territory of the Czech Republic on the date of its accession to the European Union.
Subsequently, the Czech Republic exceeded, for example, the prescribed amounts of canned mushrooms, for which it faced a heavy fine.
The survey organizers were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea and the idea of subsidies for applying for subsidies.
But these ideas came from Prague, not Brussels.
"We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
Ask the European Union for compensation," said the then Minister of Agriculture, Jaroslav Palas, in autumn 2004.
He argued that there had been a high crop of grain in the country and that, as a result of the so-called interventionist purchases, the State had had complete stocks that needed to be removed.
For being far away from the ports, the EU, according to Palas, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission responded to the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from landlocked countries.
Subsidy grants were offered to villages by the Ministry for Regional Development, led by Minister Paul Nemts (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to be applied for from Brussels.
EU: Fancy orders are an exception
While regulations in member States are easily criticized, the EU ' s regulatory efforts, as well as the European Union ' s more efficient functioning and development, are, in the view of many experts, more deserving of recognition.
A serious problem, in the view of experts, is the receipt of EU grants for projects that do not even imply anything in common with the deepening of European integration, but which member States have achieved when discussing the budget.
The Czech Republic, like other countries of the European Union, is emotional about fighting in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win in this competition.
Although the Czechs, after six years of fighting with Germans and Austrians, have retained the name "The Olomouc Cheese," but "Tuzemian rum," whose traditions in our country are rooted in the 19th century, our producers were to be renamed "Tuzemak."
Only cane dystillates can be called rum, not sugar beet.
The official list of EU registered products, along with the world-renowned "feta" and "gorgondzola" cheeses, the German Lübeck marzipan or the Parma ham, has already included, for example, carlovar suchars, the comb and Trzebon carp and the jateck ham.
The EU's trademark can also be proud of the pardubic carrot and the humps.
