Architects of MVRDV prove that real adventures are not just in the imagination - the example of Spakenissa and its recently built Book Mountain - 2 photographs
"This building seems funny to me, it looks futuristic, we can finally see something interesting again," says Lizette Verhaig, on the edge of the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a nearby large enterprise, says, "No, this building is really beautiful."
But I'm asking myself, why do we need another library today?
Everybody has Internet, iPad, and electronic books.
No one's voluntarily going to such old-fashioned libraries now, right?
Spakenisse, a small sleeping town under Rotterdam, has an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To deal with this unfortunate circumstance, several years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and to build seven fictional bridges, which are shown in euro notes, in the form of painted iron concrete miniatur.
The success of this educational initiative has been modest.
And then the city's fathers realized that they had the only way to beat the statistics: build a library here!
Wine Maas of the Rotterdam Architectural Bureau MVRDV, master of bold column diagrams and author of witty, sometimes even cynical structures, took up the task with his usual insecurities and appeared at a competition in 2003 with five books under his arm and smile on his face.
And while the members of the jury were bewilderingly looking around and shaking their shoulders, the bold Maas folded a pyramid out of his original gift in size and concluded his defense speech with the following words: "Dear citizens!"
That's my proposal: "The Book Mountain" in Spakeniss, so-called Bukenberg!
Nine years later, this 30 million euro mountain grew.
It is part of the revitalization project, which also includes an underground garage, supermarket, postage and several adjacent housing units and townhouses for a total of 50 apartments.
In early November, the Book Mountain was awarded the second award of the 2012 Best Library of the Netherlands.
The project also participates in the 2012 Dutch National Wood Construction Competition.
Thus, the faceless suburb, which had never been able to offer anything but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades suggest a milk factory, has become richer for one modern piece of architecture.
But most importantly, the first public cultural building in this town's history was created in Spakeniss.
A Long Way to the Book
First impression: Eldorado book under a cheese cap.
There's only one elevator in the center of the mountain range, because real architects and readers would prefer to explore this area on foot.
Glassed from all directions - light and easy to see, floors made of burned bricks and elegant street lights make a sense of public urban space without error.
The city environment is perfect.
Looks for the benches, dogs, and football boys and girls.
And everywhere - books, books, books.
"Ordinarily bookshelves stand along the facades, and in the middle there is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and faceless," says Vini Maas.
We've put a classic configuration of the space on the head and pulled the reading area out of the inside.
The inner space of a book mountain has been used with skill: offices, Internet library, chess club, environmental center and technical facilities.
Black bookshelves, which serve as walls, parapets, and stairwells, are particularly welcome.
Their view, texture, and smell are unusual.
Even sophisticated architects and construction engineers are lost in guesses, what kind of unknown material is that?
"We sought to work with secondary materials," explains Yop Trauborst, the project manager representing the Spakenisse community, as required by the standard.
And one day at a farm in Frisland, we met a suitable by-product of agriculture.
Artificial fibrous material of millimetre thickness has been used as a root pad in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands for many years.
It's cheap and time-saving.
Thin textiles serve one or two seasons, then they can be thrown out.
For the library, this painting - for the first time in this volume - was compressed in a panel four centimeters thick.
With heat and pressure, the so-called Landbauplastic (KLP) becomes dark, uniform, solid material, smelling a little like a new car and a little sneaker.
105 steps lead to the top.
Anyone who travels about 500 metres in length will be rewarded in a literary cafe not only with a fantastic view of the city, but also with Dutch croquettes and tree ficus in the pots.
They care about the atmosphere, and above all about the right humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
Cost of a new soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is a model environmental project," says Trouborst.
The heat of the earth shall be used for heating and cooling.
Even though the Book Mountain is under a glass cap, even in clear days the sun will only enter for a short time.
Large glued wood farms, situated perpendicular to the glass facades, provide shade and take on most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very nice.
The remaining protection is provided by fully automatic roll curtains.
Stefan Spermon, an IT skeptic mentioned above, has already visited a new library.
Lizette Verhaig has also been here.
And a traditional Chinese medicine teacher, Cynthia Bogard, who called Bukenberg "the soul of Spakenissa, which has long been missing."
Reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident was invited to contribute a book from his own congregation.
These books were supposed to be empty shelves, not yet fully staffed, with 70,000 books at the time.
The idea worked.
The shelves are all upstairs.
"There's nothing worse than a half-empty library," says architect Wine Maas.
"I think that thanks to our invitation, every resident now has some connection to this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if she only serves for jewelry.
Thus, MVRDV was able to solve a royal problem called identity creation in a professional jargon.
Spakeniss wrote his literary story.
And let them be very young and uneducated.
It's just a starting point for building an identity.
Sabo: "The Germans must play a more important role."
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
According to Stephen Sabo, the US-Europe liaison expert, in doing so, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany first indicated that it would vote against the Palestinian application for observer status with the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why?
Stephen Sabo: Germany does not support Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany now needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I do not believe that it supports the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence without speaking too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained in the vote to impose a no-fly zone.
NATO eventually implemented the proposal.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, that is, from the policy that the US was running to the German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of coherent common policies among Europeans.
Thus, the Germans are once again between the two fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I believe that as long as they only feel their role, they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy France or Britain pursues.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a position beyond the control of the US or European partners in its national interest.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, i.e. on exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany ' s economic interests differ significantly from those of other major States, and therefore Germany must defend its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced the position in the Middle East conflict and the United Nations vote?
First, Germany has large markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Gulf States.
It must therefore be careful not to offend the public and elites in the Arab world.
In any case, it plays its part.
But I wouldn't attach too much importance to it, it's not a completely one-sided connection.
But in any case, it plays an important role in German calculations.
Has Germany damaged its relations with the US by abstaining from taking important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that understanding of the German position prevails in Europe and even in the US.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Germany may even gain some respect in this way.
This signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be taken into account.
In Europe, there are differing views on the Palestinian initiative.
On the contrary, the United States has clearly expressed its support for the veto.
Are there differences of opinion between the US and many European states?
Because of American domestic policy, such differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama Government has a sufficient understanding of the European position in its heart.
But due to the local political situation, of course, the Government cannot openly take such a position.
I believe that substantive differences of opinion are not as significant as they always seem.
If you consider the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you will notice that Obama is not at all thrilled with Netanyahu's politics.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand, and the position of a key partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes the situation so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there were a single, consistent European policy, but that is not the case now.
Therefore, they cannot take a broader approach and have to act instead on their own perspectives.
That's what they do to the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take the lead in developing a common European position.
It is understandable that this is not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties with Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think it's clear to the Germans that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it really take the lead?
Or is Germany still hard to lead?
Germany is not used to it yet, it is always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is always hard to play a significant role.
Consider, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany assumes an important role, there are a variety of anti-German feelings.
It's not easy for the Germans to deal with it.
In fact, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much worse situation than the US.
It must take into account a variety of neighbours and opinions, which is not easy.
So, the US's influence in European politics is constantly weakening, but at this point the EU is not filling this vacuum, who is left behind?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, whether it's unpleasant or it's making you uncomfortable, that's life!
Stephen Sabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly explore the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Sabo is a member of the Marshall German Foundation, which specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
China's Trademark Security: When Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, also known as Polo Ralph Lauren.
But what is Armani Polo?
This is a completely official name in China that has nothing to do with the firms from whose names it is formed.
However, it will remain protected until the original names have been sued.
But it is also unclear whether they will be able to defend their rights.
"It is becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to defend their trademarks in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer for Taylor Wessing, specializing in trademark violations in the Far East.
There's a new case like this on my desk every week.
It is enough for the simulators to add just a few letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci it's Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada, you can register Prada-Kny.
In the same way, German enterprises, such as Puma, are legally copied.
Pattloch opens a folder with records from the Trademark Office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered a Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name, which also used the name of Ermenegildo Zegna's fashion house.
The Chinese are world champions of copying and violation of intellectual property rights.
In large cities, there are multi-storey department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeiting.
However, Pattloch ' s cases were not the same, and on instructions from his trustees, he was opposed to China ' s enterprises being formally authorized by the Trademark Registration Office to use a name that was already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it the Minpia Ban, the mark passenger.
This word is associated with the Ban Dakuan.
That's what women who hunt rich men are called.
Chinese authorities plead not guilty
"It hurts business, it has to be fought," Pattloch is convinced.
"The brand is blurring, the unique position is lost, the image is very much damaged."
The financial losses and procedural costs in the affected industries are estimated at millions, especially in the case of expensive copiable products.
According to the CLSA Market Research Company, China, with sales of Euro15 billion a year, is the third largest and fastest growing market for luxury goods.
However, it is difficult and expensive to obtain the removal of questionable entries in the trademark register.
The process can last up to nine years, with unclear outcomes.
Pattloch talks about cases in which the court dismissed claims because after a long period of time the contested name became a "market reality."
If the plaintiff isn't lucky, he'll even have to pay the plagiarist because he damaged his trademark in China, says Pattloch.
Sometimes it's the law of the jungle.
There are also famous graphics cases.
In 2009, Daimler lost a lawsuit with the manufacturer of Sany's construction machines, a company that had recently acquired a plant that produced the Putzmeister concretes.
Therefore, the Chinese still have the right to use a emblem similar to the Mercedes star.
The Volvo buyer Geely originally used a blue and white logo similar to the BMW; the process was successful and Geely had to change it.
Lacoste's fashioned product manufacturer lost in China to Hong Kong and Singapore's protagonists, who had a famous crocodile looking the other way.
The Chinese authorities do not feel guilty.
The CTMO Trademark Registration Office in Beijing confirms that there were difficulties in 2010 owing to lack of staff and facilities.
But last year there was a "return from emergency to normal" in the working process.
Thus, the number of pending objections cases decreased by 22 per cent.
Almost 57,000 such cases had been closed, 75 per cent more than last year.
However, 81,500 claims are still pending with the agency.
It's expensive to fight.
As is very common in China, the figures are impressive.
Last year, CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark security applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record that means that China, for the tenth consecutive time, has led a list of new registrations worldwide, reports the agency.
The same applies to the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan of fees were paid.
If simplified, this means that each registration is worth an average of 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
The appeal is worth many times more, as the German family business of Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the band has been fighting against the Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans succeeded in eliminating their illegal production of counterfeit car parts.
However, the simulator has secured Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
This was an omission of its own, as the names in Germany are not protected, says Hanno Wetzler, chairman of the Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the CTMO Trademark Registration Office rejected the Munichese claim.
True, Freudenberg won in both of the following instances, but the opposing side is still fighting.
You need to be on your guard.
The matter is currently before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler hopes to bring the matter to a good conclusion and praises the professionalism of the courts.
But he also says, "The process is extremely expensive and takes a lot of time, money, and nerves from us."
Domestic costs are unlikely to be accounted for, and the firm ' s records have even had to be reviewed for 100 years to provide evidence.
Five years ago, Freudenberg unsuccessfully offered the opposing party a "higher six-digit amount in euros" for a settlement.
"It's clear how much it costs us here," Wentzler says.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to spread even to Europe.
