The prosecutors are attempting to refute Bradley Manning ' s allegations of poor conditions of detention.
The hearing focused on Manning ' s stay in the military prison in Quantico, Virginia.
The defence demands that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning ' s detention conditions were harsh.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution attempted to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, did not take many opportunities to file a complaint of ill-treatment that he said he had been able to transfer while in a military prison.
During a cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Mide, Maryland, the military prosecutor, Major Ashden Fein, stated that the weekly visits of the prison administration to Manning during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, did not contain complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defence ' s motion to dismiss Manning ' s case on the grounds that his conditions of detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment was carried out the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in detention.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand secret documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published on the Internet on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks did not confirm that Manning was the source of the information.
During the Friday hearing, Prosecutor Fein, together with Manning, reviewed the reports that had been completed after Manning's visits by representatives of the administration during his stay in Quantico prison, where he had been under severe conditions of detention from July 2010 to April 2011.
During visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When Prosecutor Fein asked about the reports on Friday, Manning admitted that he assessed his treatment by the prison administration as "excellent" and the general conditions of detention as "very professionally organized."
The reports reviewed do not contain complaints of ill-treatment, although Manning was specifically asked about the conditions of his detention, Fane claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his oral concern about those problems and that the representatives of the Administration who visited him had discussed those problems and had stated that they would do so but had not recorded it in writing.
"They wrote "no problems" (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation," Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained about his ill-treatment in January 2011 during a meeting of the commission considering the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing a few months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting he wanted to be removed from the injury prevention regime and to ease the conditions of detention.
The military authorities explained that a limited regime of imprisonment - lower than a surveillance regime to prevent suicide - had been introduced to protect the prisoner, as well as the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I'm okay with them canceling the injury prevention regime... so my standard of life will improve, in my view," Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified to his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for almost two months before being transferred to a naval base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He reported that he had thought of suicide in Kuwait and that one day he had lost consciousness because of the heat.
He explained that it was psychologically difficult when you were not allowed to know how your fate was resolved and what was happening in the outside world.
"My world held back to Camp Arifjan base, to the size of my prison," said Manning on Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in that cage."
While in Quantico, Manning reportedly spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - alone.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to leave a mattress, blanket, slappers, some clothes and glasses.
He says that he tried to move because he could sleep or even lie down during the day, forbid the rules.
According to Manning, during his sleep, he was constantly struck with light from outside the camera.
If the guards didn't see his face when he was turning in bed at night, he said he was woke up and forced to turn over his back.
Manning ' s lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning ' s ill-treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to a military prison in Fort Livenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that, after being forced to sleep naked in his cell in Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of the guards and other prisoners during the morning inspection.
Manning said he couldn't cover up with a blanket during the check.
In response to the judge's questions on Friday, Manning said that he understood from the security officer's order that he should throw a blanket that he could cover up, but admitted that no one specifically ordered him to leave him.
On Thursday, Manning stated that the previous night he was forced to sleep naked because of his attempt to show the officer that he was not a danger to himself.
Manning said he told the officer he could use gum or scams to hurt himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slappers and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hoped that the judge would at least take into account what he had experienced during his detention and substantially reduce his sentence in the event that Manning was found guilty by a military court, which was due to start his trial early next year.
The defence stated that it was planning to ask Manning to plead guilty to less serious crimes, while other charges were being challenged as excessive.
The resumption of hearings is scheduled for this weekend, and it is expected that the prosecution will insist that the conditions of detention have been justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was detained in Quantico in accordance with the rules governing the maximum security regime for detainees.
The charges brought against Manning include aiding and abetting the enemy, illegally facilitating the publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defence and stealing State property or documents.
If convicted on all counts, he may face life imprisonment.
My crisis of national self-determination is a story from an American of Mexican origin.
In the author ' s view, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico for lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that Mexicans of American origin are torn between two cultures.
During a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked through the arrival corridor, approached the border control zone and froze on the ground.
