Old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for further peace
Is lasting peace possible between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The usual, pointless debate over who started it; many buildings were turned into ruins; over 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis were killed; for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip fell in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
However, while Israelis and Palestinians have been hopelessly trapped in their eternal conflict, changes have taken place in the Middle East.
This can be seen in different ways, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have surrounded the mutiny storm with many established realities, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay away from the whirlwind that rocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
There are, however, reasons that give rise to hope of overcoming this deadly impasse.
War without winners
At first glance, the situation is not encouraging.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on 21 November, is implemented, the clashes that took place this week have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Hamas Islamist movement that came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007 will declare that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Although some faction leaders have been destroyed and 1.7 million people blocked in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is gaining popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory now controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is working for them.
With the increasing influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world, Hamas has developed new powerful and rich friends.
Turkey ' s resurgent regional leader, once Israel ' s closest ally among Muslim countries, had supported Hamas; it had been followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic States in the Persian Gulf.
The celebratory supporters of Hamas claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel, from Lebanon in the north, ruled by Hezbollah's paramilitary group, to Syria, where the increasingly pro-Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar Assad's authority, and further to Jordan, where the King's authorities threaten Hamas's allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most densely populated and important Arab country in Egypt, where under President Mohammed Mursi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator with little focus on Hamas support.
On the other hand, Muslim brothers are an organization much similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more likely to be populist.
In future diplomatic positions, Hamas may become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the hard line in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
In a military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli anti-missile system, the Iron Dome, justified the cost of its construction and successfully destroyed many of the rockets launched by Hamas.
Israeli citizens can sleep quietly, at least for a while.
As far as diplomacy is concerned, the US has remained faithful to its constant position; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for launching the last round of violence.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, particularly under the Government of Binyamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that some 30 Israelis have been killed since 2004 by rockets fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel has been able to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, partly through the wall entering the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian State - and to protect Jewish settlements, which continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the elections scheduled for 22 January - joined with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman is very convenient.
What is the point of condoning the Palestinians and giving them their own State?
If they were to hand over all the power in the West Bank, would they start firing rockets from there towards Israel, as did their fellow citizens in the Gaza Strip?
It's better to keep them behind the wall and severely suppress any attempt to lift their heads.
The supporters of the hard line may win; however, their calculations may be refuted in the Arab spring.
While Islamists, who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere, have less affection for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
Israel's defense budget is larger than all its Arab neighbours combined.
The outbreak of a war with a regional super-Power is unlikely to help Arab Governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of President Mursi of Egypt, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to the same extent, must take into account the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic changes take place in Arab countries, depriving Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will explode sooner or later in the territories occupied by Israel, like a bus that exploded in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression was already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish State, and the demographic dimension - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbated those problems.
The bloody operations that have been carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas have to be paid for by the growing frustration of the international community.
Both sides need external momentum
The only solution that remains to be called for by sound representatives on both sides, as well as by most of the rest of the world and our newspaper, is the formation of two States and the transfer of territories by Israel in exchange for security.
There is hope, not too impressive in the short term, that the ceasefire will enable other countries to influence the parties to the conflict more effectively.
Egypt, which had long had decided to block arms transfers to the Gaza Strip, as well as Turkey and Qatar, had a better position than ever before to persuade Hamas to recognize the Jewish State ' s borders adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries must also make efforts to reconcile the Hamas and Fatah movements.
That would do more to create a Palestinian State than the forthcoming United Nations vote, which could result in recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace settlement plan.
Upon his return to the White House, he continues to show reluctance to engage in the solution of the problem.
This is a catastrophicly shortsighted attitude.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
The Uniform Package for Cigarette Act has entered into force in Australia.
Warnings of the harm caused by smoking and images of diseased body parts are contrasted with sad green boxes similar to all brands of cigarettes.
Australia ' s first worldwide law on identical packaging of cigarettes and tobacco has come into force, replacing logos and colouring with a similar box of depressing olives with creepy images of sick parts of the body and images of children whose health is affected by the smoking of their parents.
In addition to different images and signs warning against smoking, the only difference between packs that are mandatory on Saturday is the names of stamps that are printed in the same small prints.
These are the harshest tobacco packaging conditions in the world.
The Australian Federal Government states that the purpose of this measure is to discourage young people from smoking, depriving them of this harmful fashionable habit.
This decision was based on studies that showed that people who had not started smoking before the age of 26 had never become smokers in 99 out of 100 cases.
"It is clear that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging," explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia is one of the countries with the world ' s lowest share of smokers, so that these changes will not have a significant impact on the profits of transnational corporations, but other countries are already considering adopting such measures.
The tobacco industry was strongly opposed to the adoption of the law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market in which cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This law will have serious consequences different from those of its proponents," says Scott McIntyre, a representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Counterfeit producers from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For someone, on the other hand, new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha of a small family company, Zico Import Pty Ltd, claims that demand for portigar and silicon casebooks that hide unpleasant pictures on the packaging has grown rapidly (in practice from zero) since two months ago, companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their case to the High Court of Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold some 6,000 products to wholesalers and is awaiting a new shipment.
It's a good business for us.
Experts believe that the popularity of social media among the target population is a potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures.
Following the enactment of a number of laws in Australia that had made illegal television advertising and support for cigarettes, and had prohibited sellers from putting cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising had moved to the Internet.
The Australian Government has prohibited local companies and websites from posting advertisements online, but it cannot restrict foreign websites.
"If you trade tobacco products and you only have this little loophole left, the idea of promoting your product on the Internet will seem very tempting to you," explains Becky Freeman, who studied public health issues at Sydney University.
Freeman notes an increase in the number of reviews of trademarks written on behalf of alleged regular users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is it really the work of a private citizen who likes Marlboro cigarettes so much that he didn't spare time and time and made a video video, or is there a advertising company behind it?
British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more engaged in adapting to new rules than advertising.
The tobacco industry had even taken measures such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: those States were suing within the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade had been subjected to unfair restrictions, despite the fact that all those countries ' trade relations with Australia were very small.
A WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanya Plibersek, the Government had discussed with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packing laws.
In 2001, Canada first introduced mandatory smoking warning photos.
This rule has now been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening laws is being considered in Great Britain, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstrably not subject to innovation.
These pictures don't hurt me.
I'm just not paying attention.
"Just picking up a cigarette and hiding a pack in your pocket," explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on a pack.
To be honest, the only thing that can make me leave is my little girl.
James Yu, the manager of the tobacco shop King of the Pack in the centre of Sydney, claims that the same packaging made it more difficult to place the goods in the shelves.
"I've had an hour before my new shipment went off, and now it's four hours," he complains.
"The government should have taken and completely banned cigarettes, we would have said, "What to do, okay, it's over, we're closing the store," he says, throwing his hands up.
