The worst profession in the world: miners from Kawah-Ijena
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk life and health by dragging 70 kilograms of sulphur to the top of a volcano along steep rocky paths
There are people for whom their work is hell, and others literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn a living from the production of sulphur in the Kawah Ijen volcano located in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Every day Anto goes down to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphurous gas rising from the depths of the Earth freezes in contact with the air.
Large pieces of sulphur with a total weight of up to 70 kg, he puts them in two bamboo baskets, picks up baskets on his shoulders, and carries them up the cliff road.
To the top of a volcano of 2,386 metres, it is only 250 metres high, but it takes more than 40 minutes for exhausted movers to climb up with a turtle step, with difficulty in keeping their balance and a careful search of the road so that they do not retreat or fall off the cliff.
They know that one wrong move could cost them their lives, as it happened to a tourist from France who blew off the Kawah-Ijena Rock a few years ago.
Miners from Kawah-Ijen earn 5 Eurocents for each kilo of sulphur they produce.
On their way upstairs, they set themselves a road between tourists who photograph them, as if they were circus monkeys and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, walk three kilometres to the scales that the mining company laid just above, at an altitude of 1,850 metres.
This is the PT Kandi Ngribi, an enterprise that has operated this volcano since 1960 and, better or less, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 Eurocents) for each kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 Eurocents) to the petrochemical industry, as it is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As 70 kg is the norm, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) per walk," explains Anto, who usually carries three daily transfers.
He spends three hours on each of them and at the end he feels broken, but they allow him to save 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) by the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a miser for such a inhuman effort, it's three times more than he would make in the field.
"The daily payment to miners is very high by local standards, where the coffee collection is paid by Rs. 15,000 (Euro1.2) per day and the average monthly earnings equals Rs. 2 million (Euro167) ," explains a trucker who used to work as a mason on the tourist island of Bali.
His salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day and the plot was not so heavy, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a valid reason, which in Indonesia is as devastating as sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where the Hindus alone are the only ones, and brought her to Java to accept Islam."
Anto has asthma, he can barely breathe, he coughs all the time, and his eyes are tearing off because of toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Anto spent three years risking himself in Kawah Ijena, whose sulphur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special points.
He's got asthma, he's barely breathing, he's coughing, and he's got eyes tearing off because of toxic gases that produce a volcano.
That's the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
"I'll work two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French," he promises in more than acceptable English.
A life-punished, this nice and smart young man could be a tourist guide, a waiter, or a hotel porter, but instead he does a mule job.
The case of a dirty wooden cabin with other porters, it rises every day at two o'clock in the morning, because the sulphur continues to flow at night when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the midst of darkness.
In order to challenge the shadows, Anto goes down into the crater, lighting his way with a small lantern connected to his helmet, which he himself bought with his own money.
About 400 porters drag boxes of gray on their shoulders from the bottom of a volcano.
Despite the high profits, the mining company did not mechanize the production of sulphur to save costs and did not provide any equipment to porters who worked for themselves and with such deprivations.
In fact, they do not receive even a portion of the 30,000 rupees (Euro2.5) photographing fee, which, along with the 15,000 rupees (Euro1.2) entrance ticket, the guards of the reserve charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mules.
"This is a work for cattle, not for people," says Badrosin, a root porter for 42 years, who has spent three decades on Kawah-Ijean since leaving college.
A man who can lift up to 110 kilos, he assures us that he will endure the work "as long as he can ' because he needs money to educate his three children between the ages of 18 and 10.
I'm not gonna retire, I'm gonna die here because a volcano is my whole life.
Although sulphur burns the throat and burns the eyes, when the wind suddenly changes and catches miners in dense columns of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so resilient that no one complains of their serious illnesses... more serious, obviously than their usual breathing problems, arthroses, knee pains, and ulcer on their shoulders, which have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
By balancing the basket on his back, the Unainick can only lift 50 kilos in his 53 ' s.
Every day, he and his comrades carry 15 tons of sulphur from the volcano, which three trucks carry to a warehouse in Tamansari, crossing a distance of 18 kilometres along a narrow path among the bushes.
"I'm not gonna retire, I'm gonna die here because a volcano is my whole life," Unainick says, wide-opening mouth that lacks a few teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30 years old, also works as a carryer of sulphur.
Time is running out, but poverty perpetuates one of the world's hardest jobs from generation to generation: what human mules do with Kawah Ijena.
