The UNASUR Summit ends without the declaration of the Lima Declaration
The sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) was concluded today in Peru, without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, which was announced earlier and theoretically signed by the seven binding parties.
Efe has tried several times to access a document signed at the VIth Summit of Heads of State and Government of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Office of the President indicated on the front page that it would be transmitted after closure, but then confirmed that it would be published at some point on the Peruvian Government ' s website.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the contents had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollanta Umala, during brief press statements.
Journalists ' access to information about the Summit was always limited.
It was only broadcast during the day, in the press room, a video of the Presidential Assembly without sound, with a message "closed meeting, no sound."
A few of the information that was circulated among reporters was transmitted by the spokespersons of some UNASUR Governments attending the meeting, but not Peruvian.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which led to frustration among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who requested more information.
Subsequently, the Peruvian President's Administration sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is a statement by Umala, not an official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third South American and Arab Summit (ASPA), and that time the so-called Lima Declaration, which had previously been announced, was also not disseminated, despite the insistence of the press.
The official ASPA website can be checked that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities had tried to ensure that all journalists were provided with transmission systems, but had limited access to information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with a joint decision by Chile and Peru to adopt a verdict by the Hague Court, which would resolve the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Olanta Umala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which begins on Monday in The Hague, to hear the statements of both parties, in the context of the indictment that Lima filed against Santiago.
"We will respect and implement a decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently bringing before this international court," Umala said, next to his Chilean colleague.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of differences, covenants and international tribunals," Piñera added, and greeted Umala with shaking his hand against the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both Presidents that they would submit to the International Court of Justice occurred immediately after Colombia challenged this week the Pact of Bogotá, under which it recognized that the verdicts of that international court were subordinated to those of Nicaragua following a decision on maritime boundaries that it considered to be wrong.
The summit was held in the absence of the Presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rucef; Venezuela, Hugo Chávez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christine Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011, following the impeachment of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host President, Ollanta Umala, was responsible for opening the debate in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon in Lima time.
The Head of State read the outcome document, which stated that 16 agreements had been adopted and 31 projects had been approved for South American countries, with an estimated investment of $17 billion.
Among the agreements he had adopted, he mentioned that UNASUR countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding residence agreements."
He reported that action was being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against insecurity and organized transnational crime, action to increase access to medicines, affordable Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the combined and effective risks of natural disasters."
Since Europe is in crisis, "economic unification (Latin America) should not have a triumphal basis, but should serve to broaden our productive base and anticipate a better future for our cities," Umala added.
"We decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that would improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes," the Peruvian president said in the message.
Among those projects, he mentioned that five were from Peru and were limited to transverse axes on its territory, from the coast to Brazil, while two were aimed at a strong link with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The outcome document also addressed the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in that country will serve to re-accede to the Union of South American Nations," from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of well-being and peace, to be united, and to have good relations among neighbours, was another theme highlighted at the summit.
In this sense, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before participating in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet with his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner a maritime dispute as a result of the verdict of an international court contested by Bogotá.
"The day after Saturday, I might meet with President Daniel Ortega," said Santos.
"We will review all these ways, which are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua, which will require discussion with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we can handle this as civilized and respectful as possible," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they will have a new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also in the framework of the summit, the defence ministers of the bloc met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter's participation has been suspended.
Peru has a provisional presidency in the regional bloc.
