The HIV/AIDS infectionist and expert, Andrade Villanueva, explained that since 2008 scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but that the duration and quality of life depend on the extent to which the immune system is affected by patients at the start of diagnosis, with a better life expectancy for those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years, with 200 CD4s, and up to 50 years, with 500 CD4s reported.
To put it simply, the foregoing means that a person who receives a diagnosis of HIV-positive at 25 years of age, according to these terms, "by maintaining control, will be able to live without problems up to 75 years of age," he explained.
To assess this progress, it should be recalled that Mexicans today have an average life expectancy of 76 years.
